# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tone-mapping-hdr
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/display-device] A **display device** is an output device for presentation of information in visual or tactile form (the latter used for example in tactile electronic displays for blind people).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/display-device] When the input information that is supplied has an electrical signal the display is called an *electronic display*.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/display-device] Common applications for *electronic visual displays* are television sets or computer monitors.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/display-device] These are the technologies used to create the various displays in use today.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/display-device] Some displays can show only digits or alphanumeric characters.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/display-device] They are called **segment displays**, because they are composed of several segments that switch on and off to give appearance of desired glyph.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/display-device] The segments are usually single LEDs or liquid crystals.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/display-device] They are mostly used in digital watches and pocket calculators.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/display-device] Common types are seven-segment displays which are used for numerals only, and alphanumeric fourteen-segment displays and sixteen-segment displays which can display numerals and Roman alphabet letters.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/display-device] Cathode-ray tubes were also formerly widely used.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/display-device] 2-dimensional displays that cover a full area (usually a rectangle) are also called **video displays**, since it is the main modality of presenting video.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/display-device] The multiplexed display technique is used to drive most display devices.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] In photography, **exposure** is the amount of light per unit area reaching a frame of photographic film or the surface of an electronic image sensor.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] It is determined by exposure time, lens f-number, and scene luminance.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Exposure is measured in units of lux-seconds (symbol lx⋅s), and can be computed from exposure value (EV) and scene luminance in a specified region.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] An "exposure" is a single shutter cycle.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] For example, a long exposure refers to a single, long shutter cycle to gather enough dim light, whereas a multiple exposure involves a series of shutter cycles, effectively layering a series of photographs in one image.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] The accumulated *photometric exposure* (*H*v) is the same so long as the total exposure time is the same.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Only in this appropriately weighted case does the H measure the effective amount of light falling on the film, such that the characteristic curve will be correct independent of the spectrum of the light.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Many photographic materials are also sensitive to "invisible" light, which can be a nuisance , or a benefit .
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] The use of radiometric units is appropriate to characterize such sensitivity to invisible light.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] In sensitometric data, such as characteristic curves, the *log exposure* is conventionally expressed as log10(*H*).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Photographers more familiar with base-2 logarithmic scales (such as exposure values) can convert using log2(*H*) ≈ 3.32 log10(*H*).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] So-called "correct" exposure may be defined as an exposure that achieves the effect the photographer intended.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] A more technical approach recognises that a photographic film (or sensor) has a physically limited useful exposure range, sometimes called its dynamic range.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] If, for any part of the photograph, the actual exposure is outside this range, the film cannot record it accurately.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] In a very simple model, for example, out-of-range values would be recorded as "black" (underexposed) or "white" (overexposed) rather than the precisely graduated shades of colour and tone required to describe "detail".
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Therefore, the purpose of exposure adjustment (and/or lighting adjustment) is to control the physical amount of light from the subject that is allowed to fall on the film, so that 'significant' areas of shadow and highlight detail do not exceed the film's useful exposure range.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] This ensures that no 'significant' information is lost during capture.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] The photographer may carefully overexpose or underexpose the photograph to *eliminate* what they judge as insignificant or unwanted detail; to make, for example, a white altar cloth appear immaculately clean, or to emulate the heavy, pitiless shadows of film noir.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] However, it is technically much easier to discard recorded information during post processing than to try to 're-create' unrecorded information.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] In a scene with strong or harsh lighting, the *ratio* between highlight and shadow luminance values may well be larger than the ratio between the film's maximum and minimum useful exposure values.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] A photograph may be described as *overexposed* when it has a loss of highlight detail, that is, when important bright parts of an image are "washed out" or effectively all white, known as "blown-out highlights" or "clipped whites".
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] A photograph may be described as *underexposed* when it has a loss of shadow detail, that is, when important dark areas are "muddy" or indistinguishable from black, known as "blocked-up shadows" (or sometimes "crushed shadows", "crushed blacks", or "clipped blacks", especially in video).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] As the adjacent image shows, these terms are technical ones rather than artistic judgments; an overexposed or underexposed image may be "correct" in the sense that it provides the effect that the photographer intended.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Intentionally over- or underexposing (relative to a standard or the camera's automatic exposure) is casually referred to as "exposing to the right" or "exposing to the left" respectively, as these shift the histogram of the image to the right or left.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] In manual mode, the photographer adjusts the lens aperture and/or shutter speed to achieve the desired exposure.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Many photographers choose to control aperture and shutter independently because opening up the aperture increases exposure, but also decreases the depth of field, and a slower shutter increases exposure but also increases the opportunity for motion blur.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] "Manual" exposure calculations may be based on some method of light metering with a working knowledge of exposure values, the APEX system and/or the Zone System.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] A camera in **automatic exposure** or **autoexposure** (usually initialized as **AE**) mode automatically calculates and adjusts exposure settings to match (as closely as possible) the subject's mid-tone to the mid-tone of the photograph.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] For most cameras, this means using an on-board TTL exposure meter.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Aperture priority (commonly abbreviated as *A*, or *Av* for "aperture value") mode gives the photographer manual control of the aperture, whilst the camera automatically adjusts the shutter speed to achieve the exposure specified by the TTL meter.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Shutter priority (often abbreviated as *S*, or *Tv* for "time value") mode gives manual shutter control, with automatic aperture compensation.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] In each case, the actual exposure level is still determined by the camera's exposure meter.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] The purpose of an exposure meter is to estimate the subject's mid-tone luminance and indicate the camera exposure settings required to record this as a mid-tone.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] In order to do this it has to make a number of assumptions which, under certain circumstances, will be wrong.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] If the exposure setting indicated by an exposure meter is taken as the "reference" exposure, the photographer may wish to deliberately *overexpose* or *underexpose* in order to compensate for known or anticipated metering inaccuracies.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Cameras with any kind of internal exposure meter usually feature an exposure compensation setting which is intended to allow the photographer to simply offset the exposure level from the internal meter's estimate of appropriate exposure.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Frequently calibrated in stops, also known as EV units, a "+1" exposure compensation setting indicates one stop more (twice as much) exposure and "−1" means one stop less (half as much) exposure.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Exposure compensation is particularly useful in combination with auto-exposure mode, as it allows the photographer to *bias* the exposure level without resorting to full manual exposure and losing the flexibility of auto exposure.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] On low-end video camcorders, exposure compensation may be the only manual exposure control available.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] An appropriate exposure for a photograph is determined by the sensitivity of the medium used.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] For photographic film, sensitivity is referred to as film speed and is measured on a scale published by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Faster film, that is, film with a higher ISO rating, requires less exposure to make a readable image.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Digital cameras usually have variable ISO settings that provide additional flexibility.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Exposure is a combination of the length of time and the illuminance at the photosensitive material.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Exposure time is controlled in a camera by shutter speed, and the illuminance depends on the lens aperture and the scene luminance.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Slower shutter speeds (exposing the medium for a longer period of time), greater lens apertures (admitting more light), and higher-luminance scenes produce greater exposures.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] An approximately correct exposure will be obtained on a sunny day using ISO 100 film, an aperture of f/16 and a shutter speed of 1⁄100 of a second.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] This is called the sunny 16 rule: at an aperture of f/16 on a sunny day, a suitable shutter speed will be one over the film speed (or closest equivalent).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] A scene can be exposed in many ways, depending on the desired effect a photographer wishes to convey.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] An important principle of exposure is reciprocity.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] If one exposes the film or sensor for a longer period, a reciprocally smaller aperture is required to reduce the amount of light hitting the film to obtain the same exposure.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] For example, the photographer may prefer to make their sunny-16 shot at an aperture of f/5.6 (to obtain a shallow depth of field).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] As f/5.6 is 3 **stops** "faster" than f/16, with each stop meaning double the amount of light, a new shutter speed of (1⁄125)/(2·2·2) = 1⁄1000 s is needed.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Once the photographer has determined the exposure, aperture stops can be traded for halvings or doublings of speed, within limits.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] The true characteristic of most photographic emulsions is not actually linear (see sensitometry), but it is close enough over the exposure range of about 1 second to 1⁄1000 of a second.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Outside of this range, it becomes necessary to increase the exposure from the calculated value to account for this characteristic of the emulsion.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] This characteristic is known as *reciprocity failure*.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] The film manufacturer's data sheets should be consulted to arrive at the correction required, as different emulsions have different characteristics.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Digital camera image sensors can also be subject to a form of reciprocity failure.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] The Zone System is another method of determining exposure and development combinations to achieve a greater tonality range over conventional methods by varying the contrast of the film to fit the print contrast capability.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Digital cameras can achieve similar results (high dynamic range) by combining several different exposures (varying shutter or diaphragm) made in quick succession.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Today, most cameras automatically determine the correct exposure at the time of taking a photograph by using a built-in light meter, or multiple point meters interpreted by a built-in computer, see metering mode.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Negative and print film tends to bias for exposing for the shadow areas (film dislikes being starved of light), with digital favouring exposure for highlights.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Latitude is the degree by which one can over, or under expose an image, and still recover an acceptable level of quality from an exposure.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Typically negative film has a better ability to record a range of brightness than slide/transparency film or digital.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Digital should be considered to be the reverse of print film, with a good latitude in the shadow range, and a narrow one in the highlight area; in contrast to film's large highlight latitude, and narrow shadow latitude.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Slide/Transparency film has a narrow latitude in both highlight and shadow areas, requiring greater exposure accuracy.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Negative film's latitude increases somewhat with high ISO material, in contrast digital tends to narrow on latitude with high ISO settings.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Areas of a photo where information is lost due to extreme brightness are described as having "blown-out highlights" or "flared highlights".
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] In digital images this information loss is often irreversible, though small problems can be made less noticeable using photo manipulation software.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Recording to raw image format can correct this problem to some degree, as can using a digital camera with a better sensor.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Film can often have areas of extreme overexposure but still record detail in those areas.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] This information is usually somewhat recoverable when printing or transferring to digital.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] A loss of highlights in a photograph is usually undesirable, but in some cases can be considered to "enhance" appeal.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Examples include black and white photography and portraits with an out-of-focus background.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Areas of a photo where information is lost due to extreme darkness are described as "crushed blacks".
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Digital capture tends to be more tolerant of underexposure, allowing better recovery of shadow detail, than same-ISO negative print film.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/exposure-photography] Crushed blacks cause loss of detail, but can be used for artistic effect.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Graphics processor company Nvidia summarizes the motivation for HDRR in three points: bright things can be really bright, dark things can be really dark, and details can be seen in both.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The use of high-dynamic-range imaging (HDRI) in computer graphics was introduced by Greg Ward in 1985 with his open-source Radiance rendering and *lighting simulation* software which created the first file format to retain a high-dynamic-range image.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDRI languished for more than a decade, held back by limited computing power, storage, and capture methods.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Not until recently has the technology to put HDRI into practical use been developed.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In 1990, Eihachiro Nakame and associates presented a lighting model for driving simulators that highlighted the need for high-dynamic-range processing in realistic simulations.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In 1995, Greg Spencer presented *Physically-based glow visual effects for digital images* at SIGGRAPH, providing a quantitative model for flare and blooming in the human eye.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In 1997, Paul Debevec presented *Recovering high dynamic range radiance maps from photographs* at SIGGRAPH, and the following year presented *Rendering synthetic objects into real scenes*.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] These two papers laid the framework for creating HDR *light probes* of a location, and then using this probe to light a rendered scene.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDRI and HDRL (high-dynamic-range image-based lighting) have, ever since, been used in many situations in 3D scenes in which inserting a 3D object into a real environment requires the light probe data to provide realistic lighting solutions.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In gaming applications, *Riven: The Sequel to Myst* in 1997 used an HDRI postprocessing shader directly based on Spencer's paper.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] After E3 2003, Valve released a demo movie of their Source engine rendering a cityscape in a high dynamic range.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The term was not commonly used again until E3 2004, where it gained much more attention when Epic Games showcased Unreal Engine 3 and Valve announced *Half-Life 2: Lost Coast* in 2005, coupled with open-source engines such as OGRE 3D and open-source games like *Nexuiz*.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] By the 2010s, HDR displays first became available.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] With higher contrast ratios, HDRR can reduce or eliminate tone mapping, resulting in an even more realistic image.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] One of the primary advantages of HDR rendering is that details in a scene with a large contrast ratio are preserved.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Without HDRR, areas that are too dark are clipped to black and areas that are too bright are clipped to white.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] These are represented by the hardware as a floating point value of 0.0 and 1.0 for pure black and pure white, respectively.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Another aspect of HDR rendering is the addition of perceptual cues which increase apparent brightness.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDR rendering also affects how light is preserved in optical phenomena such as reflections and refractions, as well as transparent materials such as glass.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In LDR rendering, very bright light sources in a scene (such as the sun) are capped at 1.0.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] When this light is reflected the result must then be less than or equal to 1.0.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] However, in HDR rendering, very bright light sources can exceed the 1.0 brightness to simulate their actual values.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This allows reflections off surfaces to maintain realistic brightness for bright light sources.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The human eye can perceive scenes with a very high dynamic contrast ratio, around 1,000,000:1.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Adaptation is achieved in part through adjustments of the iris and slow chemical changes, which take some time (e.g. the delay in being able to see when switching from bright lighting to pitch darkness).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] At any given time, the eye's static range is smaller, around 10,000:1.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] However, this is still higher than the static range of most display technology.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Although many manufacturers claim very high numbers, plasma displays, liquid-crystal displays, and CRT displays can deliver only a fraction of the contrast ratio found in the real world, and these are usually measured under ideal conditions.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The simultaneous contrast of real content under normal viewing conditions is significantly lower.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Some increase in dynamic range in LCD monitors can be achieved by automatically reducing the backlight for dark scenes.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] For example, LG calls this technology "Digital Fine Contrast"; Samsung describes it as "dynamic contrast ratio".
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Another technique is to have an array of brighter and darker LED backlights, for example with systems developed by BrightSide Technologies.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] OLED displays have better dynamic range capabilities than LCDs, similar to plasma but with lower power consumption.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] 709 defines the color space for HDTV, and Rec.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] 2020 defines a larger but still incomplete color space for ultra-high-definition television.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Since the 2010s, OLED and other HDR display technologies have reduced or eliminated the need for tone mapping HDRR to standard dynamic range.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Light blooming is the result of scattering in the human lens, which human brain interprets as a bright spot in a scene.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] For example, a bright light in the background will appear to bleed over onto objects in the foreground.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This can be used to create an illusion to make the bright spot appear to be brighter than it really is.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Flare is the diffraction of light in the human lens, resulting in "rays" of light emanating from small light sources, and can also result in some chromatic effects.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It is most visible on point light sources because of their small visual angle.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Typical display devices cannot display light as bright as the Sun, and ambient room lighting prevents them from displaying true black.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Thus, HDR rendering systems have to map the full dynamic range of what the eye would see in the rendered situation onto the capabilities of the device.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This tone mapping is done relative to what the virtual scene camera sees, combined with several full screen effects, e.g. to simulate dust in the air which is lit by direct sunlight in a dark cavern, or the scattering in the eye.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Tone mapping and blooming shaders can be used together to help simulate these effects.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Tone mapping, in the context of graphics rendering, is a technique used to map colors from high dynamic range (in which lighting calculations are performed) to a lower dynamic range that matches the capabilities of the desired display device.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Typically, the mapping is non-linear – it preserves enough range for dark colors and gradually limits the dynamic range for bright colors.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This technique often produces visually appealing images with good overall detail and contrast.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Various tone mapping operators exist, ranging from simple real-time methods used in computer games to more sophisticated techniques that attempt to imitate the perceptual response of the human visual system.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDR displays with higher dynamic range capabilities can reduce or eliminate the tone mapping required after HDRR, resulting in an even more realistic image.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Currently HDRR has been prevalent in games, primarily for PCs but was previously prevalent in Microsoft's Xbox 360and Sony's PlayStation 3.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It has also been simulated on the PlayStation 2, GameCube, Xbox and Amiga systems.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Sproing Interactive Media had announced that their Athena game engine for the Wii will support HDRR, which added the Wii to the list of systems that support it.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In desktop publishing and gaming, color values are often processed several times over.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] As this includes multiplication and division (which can accumulate rounding errors), it is useful to have the extended accuracy and range of 16-bit integer or 16-bit floating point formats.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This is useful irrespective of the aforementioned limitations in some hardware.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Complex shader effects began their days with the release of Shader Model 1.0 with DirectX 8.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 1.0 illuminated 3D worlds with what is called standard lighting.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Lighting calculations were integer based, which didn't offer as much accuracy because the real world is not confined to whole numbers.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] On December 24, 2002, Microsoft released a new version of DirectX.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] DirectX 9.0 introduced Shader Model 2.0, which offered one of the necessary components to enable rendering of high-dynamic-range images: lighting precision was not limited to just 8-bits.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Although 8-bits was the minimum in applications, programmers could choose up to a maximum of 24 bits for lighting precision.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] However, all calculations were still integer-based.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] One of the first graphics cards to support DirectX 9.0 natively was ATI's Radeon 9700, though the effect wasn't programmed into games for years afterwards.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] On August 23, 2003, Microsoft updated DirectX to DirectX 9.0b, which enabled the Pixel Shader 2.x (Extended) profile for ATI's Radeon X series and NVIDIA's GeForce FX series of graphics processing units.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] On August 9, 2004, Microsoft updated DirectX once more to DirectX 9.0c.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This also exposed the Shader Model 3.0 profile for High-Level Shader Language (HLSL).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 3.0's lighting precision has a minimum of 32 bits as opposed to 2.0's 8-bit minimum.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Also all lighting-precision calculations are now floating-point based.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] NVIDIA states that contrast ratios using Shader Model 3.0 can be as high as 65535:1 using 32-bit lighting precision.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] At first, HDRR was only possible on video cards capable of Shader-Model-3.0 effects, but software developers soon added compatibility for Shader Model 2.0.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] As a side note, when referred to as Shader Model 3.0 HDR, HDRR is really done by FP16 blending.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] FP16 blending is not part of Shader Model 3.0, but is supported mostly by cards also capable of Shader Model 3.0 (exceptions include the GeForce 6200 series).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] FP16 blending can be used as a faster way to render HDR in video games.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 4.0 is a feature of DirectX 10, which was released with Windows Vista.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 4.0 allows 128-bit HDR rendering, as opposed to 64-bit HDR in Shader Model 3.0 (although this is theoretically possible under Shader Model 3.0).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 5.0 is a feature of DirectX 11.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It allows 6:1 compression of HDR textures without noticeable loss, which is prevalent in previous versions of DirectX HDR texture compression techniques.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It is possible to develop HDRR through GLSL shader starting from OpenGL 1.4 onwards.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/perceptual-quantizer] The **perceptual quantizer** (**PQ**), published by SMPTE as **SMPTE ST 2084,** is a transfer function that allows for HDR display by replacing the gamma curve used in SDR.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/perceptual-quantizer] Its 0–1 value range represents luminance levels from 0 to 10,000 cd/m2 (nits).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/perceptual-quantizer] It was developed by Dolby and standardized in 2014 by SMPTE and also in 2016 by ITU in Rec.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/perceptual-quantizer] ITU specifies the use of PQ or HLG as transfer functions for HDR-TV.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/perceptual-quantizer] PQ is the basis of HDR video formats (such as Dolby Vision, HDR10 and HDR10+) and is also used for HDR still picture formats.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/perceptual-quantizer] PQ is not backward compatible with the BT.1886 EOTF (i.e. the gamma curve of SDR), while HLG is compatible.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/perceptual-quantizer] PQ is a non-linear transfer function based on the human visual perception of banding and is able to produce no visible banding in 12 bits.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/perceptual-quantizer] A power function (used as EOTFs in standard dynamic range applications) extended to 10000 cd/m2 would have required 15 bits.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] In radiometry, **radiance** is the radiant flux emitted, reflected, transmitted or received by a given surface, per unit solid angle per unit projected area.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] Radiance is used to characterize diffuse emission and reflection of electromagnetic radiation, and to quantify emission of neutrinos and other particles.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] The SI unit of radiance is the watt per steradian per square metre (W·sr−1·m−2).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] It is a *directional* quantity: the radiance of a surface depends on the direction from which it is being observed.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] The related quantity spectral radiance is the radiance of a surface per unit frequency or wavelength, depending on whether the spectrum is taken as a function of frequency or of wavelength.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] Historically, radiance was called "intensity" and spectral radiance was called "specific intensity".
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] Many fields still use this nomenclature.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] It is especially dominant in heat transfer, astrophysics and astronomy.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] "Intensity" has many other meanings in physics, with the most common being power per unit area (so the radiance is the intensity per solid angle in this case).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] Radiance is useful because it indicates how much of the power emitted, reflected, transmitted, or received by a surface will be received by an optical system looking at that surface from a specified angle of view.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] In this case, the solid angle of interest is the solid angle subtended by the optical system's entrance pupil.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] Since the eye is an optical system, radiance and its cousin luminance are good indicators of how bright an object will appear.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] For this reason, radiance and luminance are both sometimes called "brightness".
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] This usage is now discouraged (see the article Brightness for a discussion).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] The nonstandard usage of "brightness" for "radiance" persists in some fields, notably laser physics.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] The radiance divided by the index of refraction squared is invariant in geometric optics.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] This means that for an ideal optical system in air, the radiance at the output is the same as the input radiance.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] This is sometimes called *conservation of radiance*.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] For real, passive, optical systems, the output radiance is *at most* equal to the input, unless the index of refraction changes.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] As an example, if you form a demagnified image with a lens, the optical power is concentrated into a smaller area, so the irradiance is higher at the image.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] The light at the image plane, however, fills a larger solid angle so the radiance comes out to be the same assuming there is no loss at the lens.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] Spectral radiance expresses radiance as a function of frequency or wavelength.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] Radiance is the integral of the spectral radiance over all frequencies or wavelengths.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] For radiation emitted by the surface of an ideal black body at a given temperature, spectral radiance is governed by Planck's law, while the integral of its radiance, over the hemisphere into which its surface radiates, is given by the Stefan–Boltzmann law.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] Its surface is Lambertian, so that its radiance is uniform with respect to angle of view, and is simply the Stefan–Boltzmann integral divided by π.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] This factor is obtained from the solid angle 2π steradians of a hemisphere decreased by integration over the cosine of the zenith angle.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] In general *L*e,Ω is a function of viewing direction, depending on *θ* through cos *θ* and azimuth angle through ∂Φe/∂Ω.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] For the special case of a Lambertian surface, ∂2Φe/(∂Ω ∂*A*) is proportional to cos *θ*, and *L*e,Ω is isotropic (independent of viewing direction).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] When calculating the radiance emitted by a source, *A* refers to an area on the surface of the source, and Ω to the solid angle into which the light is emitted.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] When calculating radiance received by a detector, *A* refers to an area on the surface of the detector and Ω to the solid angle subtended by the source as viewed from that detector.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] When radiance is conserved, as discussed above, the radiance emitted by a source is the same as that received by a detector observing it.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] As the light travels through an ideal optical system, both the étendue and the radiant flux are conserved.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] In real systems, the étendue may increase (for example due to scattering) or the radiant flux may decrease (for example due to absorption) and, therefore, basic radiance may decrease.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] However, étendue may not decrease and radiant flux may not increase and, therefore, basic radiance may not increase.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] Alternative symbols sometimes seen: W or E for radiant energy, P or F for radiant flux, I for irradiance, W for radiant exitance.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] Spectral quantities given per unit wavelength are denoted with suffix "*λ*".
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/radiance] Directional quantities are denoted with suffix "Ω".
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] It defines various aspects of HDR-TV such as display resolution (HDTV and UHDTV), frame rate, chroma subsampling, bit depth, color space, color primaries, white point, and transfer function.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] It was posted on the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) website on July 4, 2016.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] 2100 uses a wide color gamut (WCG) which is the same as Rec.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] 2100 defines two sets of HDR transfer functions which are perceptual quantization (PQ) and hybrid log-gamma (HLG).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] 2100 with a nominal peak luminance of 1,000 cd/m2 and a system gamma value that can be adjusted depending on background luminance.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] For a reference viewing environment the peak luminance of display should be 1000 cd/m2 or more for small area highlights and the black level should be 0.005 cd/m2 or less.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] The surround light should be 5 cd/m2 and be neutral grey at standard illuminant D65.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] 2100 uses the same color primaries as Rec.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] These resolutions have an aspect ratio of 16:9 and use square pixels.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] Only progressive scan frame rates are allowed.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] 2100 specifies a bit depth of either 10-bits per sample or 12-bits per sample, with either narrow range or full range color values.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] A future-use and intermediate linear RGB format using IEEE 16 bit floating point representation for each channel is also specified.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] For narrow range color, 10-bit per sample signals use video levels where the black level is defined as 64, achromatic gray level as 512 and the nominal peak as 940 in RGB, Y, and I encoding and 960 in Cb/Cr, and Ct/Cp component encoding.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] 12-bit per sample signals define 256 as the black level, 2048 as the gray level and the nominal peak is 3760 in RGB, Y, and I component encoding and 3840 in Cb/Cr, and Ct/Cp component encoding.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] Narrow range signals may extend below black or above peak white (super-black and super-white respectively), but must always be clipped to the signal range of 4-1019 for 10-bit signals or 16-4079 for 12-bit signals.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] 2100 specifies the use of RGB, YCbCr, and ICtCp.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] ICtCp provides an improved color representation that is designed for high dynamic range (HDR) and wide color gamut signals (WCG).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] 2100 allows for RGB, YCbCr, and ICtCp signal formats with 4:4:4, 4:2:2, and 4:2:0 chroma subsampling.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] 2100 specifies that if a luma (Y') signal is made it uses the same matrix coefficients as Rec.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] BT.2020 the chroma sample location that was in use was center left.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] But in H.265 (2018–02) top-left chroma siting was mandated for BT.2020-2 and BT.2100-1, that must be described in VUI (video usability information) as such.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] First value of VUI should be 2 for top-left chroma and 0 for center left.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/rec-2100] Blu-ray also uses top-left chroma for HDR, including for Dolby Vision.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The introduction of film-based photography created issues since capturing the wide dynamic range of lighting from the real world on a chemically limited negative was very difficult.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Early film developers attempted to remedy this issue by designing film stocks and print development systems that gave a desired S-shaped tone curve with slightly enhanced contrast (about 15%) in the middle range and gradually compressed highlights and shadows .
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Photographers have also used dodging and burning to overcome the limitations of the print process .
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The advent of digital photography gave hope for better solutions to this problem.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] One of the earliest algorithms employed by Land and McCann in 1971 was Retinex, inspired by theories of lightness perception .This method is inspired by the eye’s biological mechanisms of adaptation when lighting conditions are an issue.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Gamut mapping algorithms were also extensively studied in the context of color printing.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Computational models such as CIECAM02 or iCAM were used to predict color appearance.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Despite this, if algorithms could not sufficiently map tones and colors, a skilled artist was still needed, as is the case with cinematographic movie post-processing.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Computer graphic techniques capable of rendering high-contrast scenes shifted the focus from color to luminance as the main limiting factor of display devices.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Several tone mapping operators were developed to map high dynamic range images to standard displays.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] More recently, this work has branched away from utilizing luminance to extend image contrast and towards other methods such as user-assisted image reproduction.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Currently, image reproduction has shifted towards display-driven solutions since displays now possess advanced image processing algorithms that help adapt rendering of the image to viewing conditions, save power, up-scale color gamut and dynamic range.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The goals of tone mapping can be differently stated depending on the particular application.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] In some cases producing just aesthetically pleasing images is the main goal, while other applications might emphasize reproducing as many image details as possible, or maximizing the image contrast.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The goal in realistic rendering applications might be to obtain a perceptual match between a real scene and a displayed image even though the display device is not able to reproduce the full range of luminance values.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Various tone mapping operators have been developed in the recent years.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] A simple example of global tone mapping filter is $V_{\text{out}}={\frac {V_{\text{in}}}{V_{\text{in}}+1}}$ (Reinhard), where *V*in is the luminance of the original pixel and *V*out is the luminance of the filtered pixel.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Variations on this filter are commonly used in rendering.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] A perhaps more useful global tone mapping method is gamma compression, which has the filter $V_{\text{out}}=A\,V_{\text{in}}^{\gamma },$ where *A* > 0 and 0 < *γ* < 1.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] This function will map the luminance *V*in in the domain $[0,A^{-1/\gamma }]$ to the output range $[0,1].$ *γ* regulates the contrast of the image; a lower value for lower contrast.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] While a lower constant *γ* gives a lower contrast and perhaps also a duller image, it increases the exposure of underexposed parts of the image while at the same time, if *A* < 1, it can decrease the exposure of overexposed parts of the image enough to prevent them from being overexposed.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] An even more sophisticated group of tone mapping algorithms is based on contrast or gradient domain methods, which are 'local'.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Such operators concentrate on preserving contrast between neighboring regions rather than absolute value, an approach motivated by the fact that the human perception is most sensitive to contrast in images rather than absolute intensities.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Those tone mapping methods usually produce very sharp images, which preserve very well small contrast details; however, this is often done at the cost of flattening an overall image contrast, and may as a side effect produce halo-like glows around dark objects.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Examples of such tone mapping methods include: gradient domain high dynamic range compression and A Perceptual Framework for Contrast Processing of High Dynamic Range Images (a tone mapping is one of the applications of this framework).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Another approach to tone mapping of HDR images is inspired by the anchoring theory of lightness perception.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] This theory explains many characteristics of the human visual system such as lightness constancy and its failures (as in the checker shadow illusion), which are important in the perception of images.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The key concept of this tone mapping method (Lightness Perception in Tone Reproduction) is a decomposition of an HDR image into areas (frameworks) of consistent illumination and the local calculation of the lightness values.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The net lightness of an image is calculated by merging of the frameworks proportionally to their strength.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Particularly important is the anchoring—relating of the luminance to a known luminance, namely estimating which luminance value is perceived as white in the scene.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] This approach to tone mapping does not affect the local contrast and preserves the natural colors of an HDR image due to the linear handling of luminance.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] One simple form of tone mapping takes a standard image (not HDR –the dynamic range already compressed) and applies unsharp masking with a large radius, which increases local contrast rather than sharpening.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] See unsharp masking: local contrast enhancement for details.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] One of the commonly used tone mapping algorithms is the iCAM06 which is based on both the color appearance model and hierarchical mapping.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] After bilateral filtering, the image is broken into a base layer and a detail layer.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] White point adaptation and chrominance adaptation are applied to the base layer, while detail enhancement is applied to the detail layer.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Eventually the two layers are merged and converted to the IPT color space.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] In general, this method is good but has some shortcomings, specifically in how computationally heavy the filtering method is.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] A proposed solution to this involves performance optimization of the filter.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The base layer of the image is also converted to the RGB space for tone compression.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] This method also allows for more output adjustment and saturation enhancement, making it be less computationally intensive and better at reducing the overall halo effect.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Forms of tone mapping long precede digital photography.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The manipulation of film and development process to render high contrast scenes, especially those shot in bright sunlight, on printing paper with a relatively low dynamic range, is effectively a form of tone mapping, although it is not usually called that.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Local adjustment of tonality in film processing is primarily done via dodging and burning, and is particularly advocated by and associated with Ansel Adams, as described in his book *The Print;* see also his Zone System.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The normal process of exposure compensation, brightening shadows and altering contrast applied globally to digital images as part of a professional or serious amateur workflow is also a form of tone mapping.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] There are now many examples of locally tone mapped digital images, inaccurately known as "HDR photographs", on the internet, and these are of varying quality.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Although digital sensors actually capture a higher dynamic range than film, they completely lose detail in extreme highlights, clipping them to pure white, producing an unattractive result when compared with negative film, which tends to retain color and some detail in highlights.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] In some cases, tone mapped images are produced from a single exposure which is then manipulated with conventional processing tools to produce the inputs to the HDR image generation process.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] This avoids the artifacts that can appear when different exposures are combined, due to moving objects in the scene or camera shake.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] However, when tone mapping is applied to a single exposure in this way, the intermediate image has only normal dynamic range, and the amount of shadow or highlight detail that can be rendered is only that which was captured in the original exposure.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] One of the original goals of tone mapping was to be able to reproduce a given scene or image onto a display device such that the brightness sensation of the image to a human viewer closely matches the real-world brightness sensation.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] However, a perfect match for this problem is never possible and thus the output image on a display is often built from a tradeoff between different image features.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Choosing between features is often based on the necessary application, and given appropriate metrics for the application, one possible solution is to treat the issue as an optimization problem.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] For this method, models for the Human Visual System (HVS) and the display are first generated, along with a simple tone mapping operator.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The contrast distortions are weighted according to their individual visibilities approximated by the HVS.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] With these models, an objective function that defines the tone curve can be created and solved using a fast quadratic solver.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] With the addition of filters, this method can also be extended to videos.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The filters ensure that the rapid changing of the tone-curve between frames are not salient in the final output image.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The images on the right show the interior of a church, a scene which has a variation in radiance much larger than that which can be displayed on a monitor or recorded by a conventional camera.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The six individual exposures from the camera show the radiance of the scene in some range transformed to the range of brightnesses that can be displayed on a monitor.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The range of radiances recorded in each photo is limited, so not all details can be displayed at once: for example, details of the dark church interior cannot be displayed at the same time as those of the bright stained-glass window.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] An algorithm is applied to the six images to recreate the high dynamic range radiance map of the original scene (a high dynamic range image).
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Alternatively, some higher-end consumer and specialist scientific digital cameras are able to record a high dynamic range image directly, for example with RAW images.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] The high dynamic range image is passed to a tone mapping operator, in this case a local operator, which transforms the image into a low dynamic range image suitable for viewing on a monitor.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Relative to the church interior, the stained-glass window is displayed at a much lower brightness than a linear mapping between scene radiance and pixel intensity would produce.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] However, this inaccuracy is perceptually less important than the image detail, which can now be shown in both the window and the church interior simultaneously.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] These results are caused by application of geometric space distortion of captured image along with color space distortion, while only color space distortions are a tone mapping effect, and all other distortions are rather a custom filtering technique than any tone or color space mapping.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] So, the results of local tone mapping are often judged as perverting the nature of a documentalist photographic image and far from photographic realism.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Not all tone mapped images are visually distinctive.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Reducing dynamic range with tone mapping is often useful in bright sunlit scenes, where the difference in intensity between direct illumination and shadow is great.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] In these cases the global contrast of the scene is reduced, but the local contrast maintained, while the image as a whole continues to look natural.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Tone mapping can also produce distinctive visual effects in the final image, such as the visible halo around the tower in the Cornell Law School image in the thumbnail.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] It can be used to produce these effects even when the dynamic range of the original image is not particularly high.
[src:tone-mapping-hdr/tone-mapping] Usually this effect is subtle, but if the contrasts in the original image are extreme, or the photographer deliberately sets the luminance gradient to be very steep, the halos become visible.
